"is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "H4", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2171, "end": 2173}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testis nuclei", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7658399343490601, "span": {"begin": 2177, "end": 2190}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9734"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HDAC", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9896047115325928, "span": {"begin": 2213, "end": 2217}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:39867"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "valproic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988952875137329, "span": {"begin": 2240, "end": 2253}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:39867"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "VPA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996359348297119, "span": {"begin": 2255, "end": 2258}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54145"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5768227577209473, "span": {"begin": 2269, "end": 2276}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mouse teratocarcinoma cell line F9", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9712123870849609, "span": {"begin": 2297, "end": 2331}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mouse", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.990706741809845, "span": {"begin": 2297, "end": 2302}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "teratocarcinoma cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5415576696395874, "span": {"begin": 2303, "end": 2323}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018243"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "teratocarcinoma", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9221359491348267, "span": {"begin": 2303, "end": 2318}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "F9", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5331541299819946, "span": {"begin": 2329, "end": 2331}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3020", "3021"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histone H3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9805460572242737, "span": {"begin": 2375, "end": 2385}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HDAC1-deficient ES cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9307069778442383, "span": {"begin": 2402, "end": 2426}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3065"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HDAC1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9894994497299194, "span": {"begin": 2402, "end": 2407}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "-deficient ES cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5728632211685181, "span": {"begin": 2407, "end": 2426}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:35738"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MAA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994818568229675, "span": {"begin": 2468, "end": 2471}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54145"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9794932007789612, "span": {"begin": 2480, "end": 2487}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8350"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "H3K9Ac", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9921197891235352, "span": {"begin": 2503, "end": 2509}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:85235"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "H4K12Ac", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9716582894325256, "span": {"begin": 2514, "end": 2521}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:27067"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "p53K379Ac", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9963914752006531, "span": {"begin": 2534, "end": 2543}}], "text": "The major empirical evidence came from the incubation of cell culture cells with small molecule compounds that inhibit HDAC enzymes followed by western blots or acid urea gel analysis. The first evidence was shown by Riggs et al. who showed that incubation of HeLa cells with n-butyrate leads to an accumulation of acetylated histone proteins [Riggs et al., 1977]. Later, it was shown that n-butyrate specifically increases the acetylation of histone by the incorporation of radioactive [3H]acetate and analysis of the histones on acid urea gels that allow the detection of acetylated histones [Cousens et al., 1979]. TSA was shown to be an HDAC inhibitor by acid urea gel analysis in 1990 [Yoshida et al., 1990] and good evidence for VPA as an HDAC inhibitor in vitro and in vivo was shown using acetyl-specific antibodies and western blot [Gottlicher et al., 2001].  There exist several pieces of evidence showing the link between histone deacetylase inhibition and increase in histone acetylation as follows:    Exposure of mouse embryos in utero to VPA and TSA (two well-known HDAC inhibitors) showed an increased histone acetylation level in whole embryo extracts and was also shown in situ immuno-stainings [Menegola et al., 2005].  HDAC inhibition by HDIs leads to hyperacetylation of histone and a large number of cellular proteins such as NF-kappaB [Falkenberg and Johnstone, 2014; Chen et al., 2018].  The concentrations of half-maximum inhibitory effect (IC50) for HDAC enzyme inhibition of 20 valproic acid derivatives correlated with teratogenic potential of the compounds, and HDAC inhibitory compounds showed hyperacetylation of core histone 4 in treated F9 cells [Eikel et al., 2006].  HDIs increase histone acetylation in the brain [Schroeder et al., 2013].  More acetylation sites on the histones H3 and H4 are responsive to SAHA than to MS-275 indicating that an HDI selectivity exists [Choudhary et al., 2009].  HDI AR-42 induces acetylation of histone H3 in a dose-response manner in human pancreatic cancer cell lines [Henderson et al., 2016].  MAA treatment in rats (650 mg/kg, for 4, 8, 12, and 24 hrs) induced hyperacetylation in histones H3 and H4 of testis nuclei [Wade et al., 2008].  HDAC inhibition induced by valproic acid (VPA) leads to histone hyperacetylation in mouse teratocarcinoma cell line F9 [Eikel et al., 2006].  Hyperacetylation of histone H3 was observed in HDAC1-deficient ES cells [Lagger et al., 2002].  The treatment of MAA induced histone acetylation in H3K9Ac and H4K12Ac, as well as p53K379Ac [Dayan and Hales, 2014].   &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:00:48 +0000 2026"}